1
00:00:00,064 --> 00:00:01,524
<i>Previously on "Suits"...</i>

2
00:00:01,526 --> 00:00:03,579
<i>Rachel,</i>
<i>it's Professor Dunbar.</i>

3
00:00:03,679 --> 00:00:05,657
I was wondering if you'd
be interested in helping me

4
00:00:05,681 --> 00:00:07,114
<i>with the Innocence Project.</i>

5
00:00:07,149 --> 00:00:09,094
You want me to help you get
an innocent man off death row?

6
00:00:09,118 --> 00:00:10,084
<i>What do you want, Harvey?</i>

7
00:00:10,119 --> 00:00:11,418
Help me protect Mike Ross.

8
00:00:11,454 --> 00:00:12,564
He's in there
with a guy I put away,

9
00:00:12,588 --> 00:00:13,554
and the guy is no joke.

10
00:00:13,589 --> 00:00:14,955
What am I supposed to do?

11
00:00:14,991 --> 00:00:17,224
You're supposed to move
the guy to another prison.

12
00:00:17,259 --> 00:00:18,826
You want me one-on-one?
You got it.

13
00:00:18,861 --> 00:00:20,794
I'm gonna use this,
and they're gonna hold you.

14
00:00:20,830 --> 00:00:22,162
- No!
- What's going on here?

15
00:00:22,198 --> 00:00:23,731
<i>[tense music]</i>

16
00:00:23,766 --> 00:00:25,165
Why'd you come back
with a guard?

17
00:00:25,201 --> 00:00:26,712
I didn't do it
to get you to forgive me.

18
00:00:26,736 --> 00:00:28,780
I never should have let him
in here in the first place.

19
00:00:28,804 --> 00:00:30,537
The time you served
while awaiting trial

20
00:00:30,573 --> 00:00:32,473
was never factored
into your sentence.

21
00:00:32,508 --> 00:00:34,274
You're eligible for
parole in six weeks.

22
00:00:34,310 --> 00:00:36,410
You think I don't know
this is your protector's idea

23
00:00:36,445 --> 00:00:37,544
to get me off your back?

24
00:00:37,580 --> 00:00:38,812
Nah, Frank.

25
00:00:38,848 --> 00:00:41,248
Harvey's idea was for me
to tell these guys

26
00:00:41,283 --> 00:00:42,449
that you're an informant.

27
00:00:42,485 --> 00:00:44,351
I figured out a way
to get Mike out early.

28
00:00:44,387 --> 00:00:45,352
What's the catch?

29
00:00:45,388 --> 00:00:46,687
He has to inform
on his roommate.

30
00:00:46,722 --> 00:00:48,222
Mike gets him to turn,
he's free.

31
00:00:48,257 --> 00:00:49,490
When do you need an answer by?

32
00:00:49,525 --> 00:00:50,624
Yesterday.

33
00:00:50,660 --> 00:00:51,959
And the answer needs to be yes.

34
00:00:51,994 --> 00:00:52,994
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35
00:00:54,930 --> 00:00:55,963
Harvey, wait a second.

36
00:00:55,998 --> 00:00:56,964
Where are you going?

37
00:00:56,999 --> 00:00:58,143
Where do you think I'm going?

38
00:00:58,167 --> 00:00:59,199
I'm gonna see Mike.

39
00:00:59,235 --> 00:01:00,612
And I know what
you're going to say,

40
00:01:00,636 --> 00:01:02,703
but Mike went to prison
so we wouldn't have to,

41
00:01:02,738 --> 00:01:04,972
and now he's in danger
from a guy I put away.

42
00:01:05,007 --> 00:01:07,341
So you'll forgive me if
I don't stand around and wait

43
00:01:07,376 --> 00:01:08,776
for you to drop the hammer.

44
00:01:08,811 --> 00:01:11,211
You think I like the idea
of him rotting in that place?

45
00:01:11,247 --> 00:01:12,713
But if you want
this thing to work,

46
00:01:12,748 --> 00:01:14,893
you can't go running up there
in the middle of the night.

47
00:01:14,917 --> 00:01:16,850
You heard Cahill.
He needs an answer yesterday.

48
00:01:16,886 --> 00:01:18,886
What he needs is results.

49
00:01:18,921 --> 00:01:20,699
And if Mike's lawyer
pulls him out of his cell

50
00:01:20,723 --> 00:01:22,467
in the middle of the night,
then his roommate

51
00:01:22,491 --> 00:01:24,124
is going to sense
there's something wrong

52
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:26,894
before this thing
even gets started.

53
00:01:26,929 --> 00:01:29,830
Fine, but I'm going up there
first thing in the morning,

54
00:01:29,865 --> 00:01:32,332
and nothing you say
is going to stop me.

55
00:01:32,368 --> 00:01:39,373
<i>♪ ♪</i>

56
00:01:40,376 --> 00:01:41,742
Can't sleep?

57
00:01:41,777 --> 00:01:43,210
Not really.

58
00:01:43,245 --> 00:01:44,778
Well, as long as you're up,

59
00:01:44,814 --> 00:01:45,779
might want to think about

60
00:01:45,815 --> 00:01:47,681
putting up some
pictures of your own.

61
00:01:47,717 --> 00:01:50,851
That way, you won't have
to keep staring at mine.

62
00:01:54,790 --> 00:01:57,925
How old are they?

63
00:01:57,960 --> 00:02:00,594
Maddy is seven.

64
00:02:00,629 --> 00:02:03,263
Nate just turned five.

65
00:02:03,299 --> 00:02:05,499
They look really sweet.

66
00:02:05,534 --> 00:02:08,869
Yeah...they're great.

67
00:02:08,904 --> 00:02:10,704
How often do you
get to see 'em?

68
00:02:10,740 --> 00:02:12,250
- I don't.
- What do you mean you don't?

69
00:02:12,274 --> 00:02:13,240
Bad divorce or something?

70
00:02:13,275 --> 00:02:15,008
Nah, nah,
nothing like that.

71
00:02:15,044 --> 00:02:16,844
We've been married
for ten years.

72
00:02:16,879 --> 00:02:18,390
I just--I just don't
let 'em come here.

73
00:02:18,414 --> 00:02:19,613
What?
Why not?

74
00:02:19,648 --> 00:02:21,515
They shouldn't see
their father as a criminal.

75
00:02:21,550 --> 00:02:22,516
Kevin, come on, man.

76
00:02:22,551 --> 00:02:23,717
I know it's hard on them.

77
00:02:23,753 --> 00:02:25,652
It tears me up every
single day that I'm here.

78
00:02:25,688 --> 00:02:29,156
But they're kids.
They're resilient.

79
00:02:29,191 --> 00:02:30,758
Yeah, I wouldn't be so sure.

80
00:02:30,793 --> 00:02:32,092
Well, Mike,
you don't have kids.

81
00:02:32,128 --> 00:02:33,128
So you don't know.

82
00:02:33,162 --> 00:02:34,461
No.
I don't.

83
00:02:34,497 --> 00:02:37,264
But I do know what it's like
to be a kid missing his dad.

84
00:02:37,299 --> 00:02:40,467
Please don't tell me your
old man abandoned the family.

85
00:02:40,503 --> 00:02:45,305
Both of my parents died
in a car accident when I was 11.

86
00:02:45,341 --> 00:02:47,307
Hit by a drunk driver.

87
00:02:47,343 --> 00:02:50,444
Jesus, that's...
I'm sorry, Mike.

88
00:02:50,479 --> 00:02:52,312
<i>[somber music]</i>

89
00:02:52,348 --> 00:02:55,549
Yeah, it was a long time ago.

90
00:02:55,584 --> 00:02:57,384
Kevin, I understand
the instinct to protect

91
00:02:57,419 --> 00:02:59,887
your children, but what are
you protecting them from?

92
00:02:59,922 --> 00:03:01,188
What do you mean?

93
00:03:01,223 --> 00:03:02,956
I mean we've been
roommates for a while now.

94
00:03:02,992 --> 00:03:06,093
Don't you think it's time you
told me what you're in here for?

95
00:03:06,128 --> 00:03:07,661
[door buzzes]

96
00:03:07,696 --> 00:03:09,029
Hey, Ross.

97
00:03:09,064 --> 00:03:10,130
Your lawyer's here.

98
00:03:10,166 --> 00:03:11,665
- Now?
- I'm just the messenger.

99
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:13,667
You want out of this box or not?

100
00:03:13,702 --> 00:03:21,708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

101
00:03:34,356 --> 00:03:36,190
Mr. Bailey, my name
is Rachel Zane.

102
00:03:36,225 --> 00:03:37,791
I am a law student at Columbia,

103
00:03:37,827 --> 00:03:39,626
and I'm here to talk
to you about your case.

104
00:03:39,662 --> 00:03:40,794
Student?

105
00:03:40,830 --> 00:03:42,763
Yes, we work alongside
the Innocence Project

106
00:03:42,798 --> 00:03:44,810
to determine if you have
the criteria for an appeal.

107
00:03:44,834 --> 00:03:47,634
Do you know how long
I've been sittin' on death row?

108
00:03:47,670 --> 00:03:49,636
12 years.
I read your file.

109
00:03:49,672 --> 00:03:52,206
And for the last ten of 'em,
I've been writing letters

110
00:03:52,241 --> 00:03:55,943
and begging any lawyer
to listen to my story.

111
00:03:55,978 --> 00:03:59,213
And they finally get around
to getting back to me,

112
00:03:59,248 --> 00:04:01,081
and they don't even
have the courtesy

113
00:04:01,116 --> 00:04:03,016
of sendin' me a real lawyer?

114
00:04:03,052 --> 00:04:06,386
Mr. Bailey, trust me,
I will fight for you.

115
00:04:06,422 --> 00:04:08,522
You're a student.

116
00:04:08,557 --> 00:04:11,859
You can't do shit for me.

117
00:04:11,894 --> 00:04:14,428
Well, you know what?
You killed two people.

118
00:04:14,463 --> 00:04:16,830
In cold blood.

119
00:04:16,866 --> 00:04:19,233
You know it, and I know it,
and that's why you're in there,

120
00:04:19,268 --> 00:04:20,934
so thank you
for making the decision

121
00:04:20,970 --> 00:04:23,871
to not take your case
an easy one.

122
00:04:23,906 --> 00:04:25,205
You don't know me.

123
00:04:25,241 --> 00:04:29,343
All you know is what you
read in some damn file.

124
00:04:29,378 --> 00:04:31,478
I didn't kill anyone.

125
00:04:31,513 --> 00:04:34,314
I've been saying it for 12 years
and I can prove it.

126
00:04:34,350 --> 00:04:35,315
You're right.

127
00:04:35,351 --> 00:04:36,516
I don't know you.

128
00:04:36,552 --> 00:04:39,186
And you don't know me either.

129
00:04:39,221 --> 00:04:43,357
So do you want to take
a chance on each other or not?

130
00:04:43,392 --> 00:04:48,262
I need help, Ms. Zane.

131
00:04:48,297 --> 00:04:49,730
<i>♪ ♪</i>

132
00:04:49,765 --> 00:04:52,199
So let me help you.

133
00:04:52,234 --> 00:04:55,335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

134
00:04:55,371 --> 00:04:56,403
[door opens]

135
00:04:56,438 --> 00:04:57,738
Harvey, what are
you doing here?

136
00:04:57,773 --> 00:04:59,573
There's something I need
to talk to you about.

137
00:04:59,608 --> 00:05:00,574
Sit down.

138
00:05:00,609 --> 00:05:03,377
What is it?

139
00:05:03,412 --> 00:05:05,112
I just got a visit
from Sean Cahill.

140
00:05:05,147 --> 00:05:06,446
About Gallo?

141
00:05:06,482 --> 00:05:07,959
I thought you said
he can't get him transferred.

142
00:05:07,983 --> 00:05:09,549
He can't, but it turns out

143
00:05:09,585 --> 00:05:10,795
there's a way
he can get you out.

144
00:05:10,819 --> 00:05:11,919
What do you mean "out"?

145
00:05:11,954 --> 00:05:15,055
I mean out, as in
you walk out that front door

146
00:05:15,090 --> 00:05:17,324
and you never look back.

147
00:05:17,359 --> 00:05:18,792
- What's the catch?
- Mike--

148
00:05:18,827 --> 00:05:20,872
Harvey, you're not here
telling me that I can get out

149
00:05:20,896 --> 00:05:21,862
with that look on your face

150
00:05:21,897 --> 00:05:23,074
if there isn't something else.

151
00:05:23,098 --> 00:05:24,665
He needs you to inform
on your cellmate.

152
00:05:24,700 --> 00:05:25,732
What?

153
00:05:25,768 --> 00:05:27,178
If whatever you get
leads to a conviction

154
00:05:27,202 --> 00:05:28,368
on his father-in-law,

155
00:05:28,404 --> 00:05:30,671
he'll commute your sentence
and you get to walk.

156
00:05:30,706 --> 00:05:32,306
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

157
00:05:32,341 --> 00:05:34,107
- What'd the guy do?
- Who cares what he did?

158
00:05:34,143 --> 00:05:35,676
I care,
because if it was so bad,

159
00:05:35,711 --> 00:05:37,255
why didn't Kevin turn on him
in the first place?

160
00:05:37,279 --> 00:05:38,245
Mike, what does it matter?

161
00:05:38,280 --> 00:05:39,280
He can get you out.

162
00:05:39,315 --> 00:05:41,114
This is my only
friend in here.

163
00:05:41,150 --> 00:05:42,115
I'm not gonna betray him.

164
00:05:42,151 --> 00:05:43,684
Friend?
Listen to me, God damn it.

165
00:05:43,719 --> 00:05:45,519
There's someone in here
trying to kill you

166
00:05:45,554 --> 00:05:46,720
and I'm giving you a way out.

167
00:05:46,755 --> 00:05:47,755
I'm taking care of Gallo.

168
00:05:47,790 --> 00:05:49,000
What the hell is that
supposed to mean?

169
00:05:49,024 --> 00:05:50,602
It means that I did
what you told me to do.

170
00:05:50,626 --> 00:05:52,671
I threatened to tell people
that he was an informant,

171
00:05:52,695 --> 00:05:55,028
but what I also did was found
out a way to get him parole.

172
00:05:55,064 --> 00:05:56,763
